    "faqs_jWyqCp": {
      "type": "faq-section",
      "blocks": {
        "faq_item_Xa7a9G": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "faq_question": "Can I wear white gold if I have a nickel allergy?",
            "faq_answer": "<p>We generally advise against it. White gold is often alloyed with nickel to bleach the yellow color out of the gold. While Rhodium plating protects your skin initially, once that plating wears off, the nickel can cause irritation. If you have sensitive skin, Platinum is the only 100% safe choice.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_item_rcaANV": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "faq_question": "Does a platinum ring require more maintenance than gold?",
            "faq_answer": "<p>It depends on your aesthetic preference. If you want your ring to look \"mirror shiny\" forever, platinum requires more maintenance, such as frequent polishing, because it dulls quickly. However, if you don't mind the matte patina, platinum is effectively low maintenance because it doesn't require the chemical re-plating that white gold needs.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_item_HMGtjz": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "faq_question": "Is it difficult to resize platinum later?",
            "faq_answer": "<p>Yes, it is more labor-intensive than gold. Because platinum requires such high heat, it cannot be soldered with a standard torch easily. It usually requires a laser welder to ensure the join line is invisible. While any competent jeweler can resize gold, you should only trust a specialist with platinum</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_item_UHKzLJ": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "faq_question": "Why does my white gold ring look yellow after a year?",
            "faq_answer": "<p>This is normal wear and tear. White gold is naturally a creamy, warm champagne color. The \"bright white\" look comes from Rhodium plating. As you wear the ring, friction rubs this plating off. A simple \"dip\" at the jeweler will restore it to brand-new condition instantly.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
